Answer: Here is a basic Maven `pom.xml` template for compiling a Java project:

```xml
<project xmlns="http://maven.apache.org/POM/4.0.0" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
  xsi:schemaLocation="http://maven.apache.org/POM/4.0.0 http://maven.apache.org/xsd/maven-4.0.0.xsd">
    <modelVersion>4.0.0</modelVersion>

    <groupId>com.example</groupId>
    <artifactId>my-java-project</artifactId>
    <version>1.0-SNAPSHOT</version>
    <packaging>jar</packaging>

    <name>My Java Project</name>
    <description>This is my Java project.</description>

    <properties>
        <project.build.sourceEncoding>UTF-8</project.build.sourceEncoding>
        <maven.compiler.source>1.8</maven.compiler.source>
        <maven.compiler.target>1.8</maven.compiler.target>
    </properties>

    <dependencies>
        <!-- Add your dependencies here -->
    </dependencies>

    <build>
        <plugins>
            <plugin>
                <groupId>org.apache.maven.plugins</groupId>
                <artifactId>maven-compiler-plugin</artifactId>
                <version>3.8.1</version>
                <configuration>
                    <source>${maven.compiler.source}</source>
                    <target>${maven.compiler.target}</target>
                </configuration>
            </plugin>
        </plugins>
    </build>
</project>
```

The LCD control system using a potentiometer and temperature sensor is a project that involves using an Arduino board to read temperature from a temperature sensor and display it on an LCD screen. The system also uses a potentiometer to control the brightness of the LCD panel.

To set up the system, the temperature sensor, such as the LM35, is connected to the Arduino board via VCC and GND pins, and the analog output pin of the sensor is connected to the analog input pin A0 of the Arduino [[3](https://www.hackatronic.com/arduino-with-temperature-sensor-interfacing-lcd-and-lm35/)]. The LCD screen is connected to the Arduino board, and a 10 K Ohm potentiometer is used to control the brightness of the panel [[3](https://www.hackatronic.com/arduino-with-temperature-sensor-interfacing-lcd-and-lm35/)].

To program the Arduino board, the LiquidCrystal_I2C library is installed, and the code is uploaded to the board [[2](https://arduinogetstarted.com/tutorials/arduino-display-temperature-from-lm35-sensor-on-lcd)]. The code reads the temperature from the sensor and displays it on the LCD screen. The potentiometer is used to control the brightness of the panel by adjusting the voltage supply to the LCD screen.

A detailed tutorial on how to set up and program the system can be found on ArduinoGetStarted [[1](https://arduinogetstarted.com/tutorials/arduino-temperature-sensor-lcd)]. The tutorial provides a step-by-step guide on how to combine the temperature sensor code and LCD code, and how to program the Arduino board.

## Step 1: Define the problem and the desired outcome
We need to sort an array of strings in a case-insensitive manner, meaning that uppercase and lowercase letters should be treated equally.

## Step 2: Choose a sorting method
JavaScript's built-in `sort()` method can be used to sort arrays. However, by default, it sorts strings in a case-sensitive manner. To achieve case-insensitive sorting, we can use the `localeCompare()` method or provide a custom comparison function to the `sort()` method.

## Step 3: Use the localeCompare() method or a custom comparison function
We can use the `localeCompare()` method to compare strings in a case-insensitive manner. Alternatively, we can provide a custom comparison function to the `sort()` method that converts both strings to lowercase or uppercase before comparing them.

## Step 4: Implement the solution
Here is an example implementation using the `localeCompare()` method:
```javascript
const arr = ["Zebra", "apple", "Cat", "dog", "Elephant"];
arr.sort((a, b) => a.localeCompare(b, undefined, { sensitivity: 'base' }));
console.log(arr); // Output: ["apple", "Cat", "dog", "Elephant", "Zebra"]
```

To configure Apache Airflow to support Azure Active Directory (AAD) Single Sign-On (SSO) tokens, you will need to set up OAuth2 authentication in Airflow. This involves configuring Airflow to use Azure AD as an OAuth2 provider. Below is a step-by-step guide to help you generate the necessary configuration code for your `airflow.cfg` file.

### Prerequisites

1. **Azure Active Directory (AAD) Setup**: Ensure you have an Azure Active Directory set up and have registered an application in Azure AD. This application will be used for OAuth2 authentication.
2. **Client ID and Client Secret**: Obtain the Client ID and Client Secret from your Azure AD application registration. You will need these for the configuration.
3. **Tenant ID**: Note down your Azure AD Tenant ID.
4. **Redirect URI**: Configure a redirect URI in your Azure AD application settings. This should match the URI that Airflow will use to receive the authorization code.

### Configuration Steps

1. **Enable OAuth2 in Airflow**:

   ```ini
[api]

[core]
```
